		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper19</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>Modular Well-Definedness Analysis for Attribute Grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/TedKaminski.html">Ted Kaminski</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_20">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_20</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is an analysis of language definitions (attribute grammars) ensuring completeness and non-circularity.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It is explicitly modular, enabling independent extension modules to be checked locally while guaranteeing global properties.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The work is grounded in an extensible attribute-grammar meta-language (Silver) and its modular composition model.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Ensuring well-definedness properties is a formal correctness task with conservative analyses and associated arguments.
</li></ul></li></ul>
